  "prompt": "If I saw a crime being perpetrated and I didn't report it, could I go to jail?",
  "response": "In some jurisdictions, there are laws that require individuals to report certain types of crimes, especially those involving harm to others or serious offenses. These are often referred to as \"mandatory reporting\" laws. However, in many places, there is no general legal obligation for a bystander to report a crime they witness, unless they fall into specific categories, such as being a mandated reporter (e.g., teachers, doctors, or social workers).\n\nIf you fail to report a crime in a jurisdiction where there is a legal obligation to do so, you could potentially face legal consequences, including fines or jail time, depending on the severity of the unreported crime and the specific laws in your area.\n\nIt's important to check the laws in your specific location, as they can vary widely. If you're concerned about a situation you've witnessed, it might be wise to consult with a legal professional who can provide advice based on the laws applicable to your situation.",
